com.symbian.commdb.data
Class Database

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.symbian.commdb.data.Database
public class Database
extends java.lang.Object

This class contains all the CommDB tables. The structure of these tables is determined by the processing of a set of XML Schema files which specify the CommDB database. These files should all reside in the same directory or subdirectories of the same directory.

AddXMLSchemaFileName

public boolean AddXMLSchemaFileName(java.lang.String fileName,
                                    java.lang.String tableTemplateName,
                                    java.lang.String tableName,
                                    java.lang.String enumerationFileName)
Add an XML Schema file name in the database list. This name may contain the subdirectory of the XML Schema directory the file resides i.e. [m_schemaDirectory]\[subdirectory\filename] { --- fileName ---- } At the same time, the name of the table template corresponding to this file must be supplied e.g. fileName = "IAPTable.xsd" tableNTemplateName = "IAP" tableName = "IAPTable"

Parameters:
fileName - The name of the XML Schema file to add
tableTemplateName - The name of the table template corresponding to this XML Schema file
tableName - The name of the table corresponding to this XML Schema file
enumerationFileName - The name of the XML Schema file with the definition of the enumerations
Returns:
True if the operation was successful, false if not

FindBrokenTableEntryLinks

public boolean FindBrokenTableEntryLinks(java.util.Vector brokenParams,
                                         java.util.Vector brokenLinks)
This method examines the table entry parameters which expect as a value a table entry link, for all tables in the database, and finds all broken references.

Parameters:
brokenParams - A vector with all the qualified names of all parameters with invalid table entry references
brokenLinks - A vector with all the qualified names of the invalid table entries
Returns:
True if the table entry references are all valid, false in the opposite case.
